Marston, too, lingered over the allusion to Rome, and hence these magnificent lines :—

Erictho. Know then, our love, hard by the reverent ruins Of a once glorious temple rear‘d to Jove, Whose very rubbish (like the pitied fall Of virtue most unfortunate) yet bears A deathless majesty, though now quite razed, &a “Sophonisba,” IV. i. 144-8.

The parallels in Montaigne and Marston are so numerous and so close that I find it will save time and labour to students ifI record them as they occur in Marston’s work. Only close or interesting coinci- dences in the two authors will be noticed, and those that have already been dealt with will, of course, be excluded from the list, which is far from being com- plete.
